9. Testing Steps
Save the updated SNS contact point message body.
Confirm the Airflow High CPU Utilization alert rule uses the same contact point.
Trigger, preview, or wait for the alert to fire.
Verify that SNS receives a JSON message body.
Verify that SQS receives the same JSON body.
Ask the Lambda developer to confirm that json.loads(message) succeeds.
Verify that the internal alert system creates or updates the alert.
10. Expected End-to-End Flow
Grafana alert fires
  -> SNS message body is valid JSON
  -> SQS receives JSON string
  -> Lambda parses the JSON
  -> Lambda maps labels and annotations
  -> Internal alert is created or updated
  -> Alert is visible in the internal alert UI
11. Grafana-Side Checklist
Alert name is Airflow High CPU Utilization.
Contact point is EXAMPLE-PRD-Alerts-SNS-INTERNAL.
Contact point type is AWS SNS.
SNS contact point Message field contains the custom JSON template.
Alert labels include component, account_id, resource, region, stage, and subsys.
The message body is valid JSON after Grafana template rendering.
The Lambda developer confirms that the payload can be parsed and mapped.
12. Notes for Lambda Developer
The Grafana side will send a JSON object with an alerts array. Each alert includes status, labels, and annotations. The Lambda should parse the SNS/SQS message body and map these fields to the internal alert format.
status -> alert state, for example firing or resolved
labels.alertname -> internal alert title/name
labels.component -> owning component
labels.account_id -> cloud account identifier
labels.resource -> affected resource
labels.region -> cloud region
labels.stage -> environment/stage
labels.subsys -> subsystem or service family
annotations.description -> human-readable alert description
